            <div type="typology">
               <head>Typology (Local)</head>
               <p rend="typology" xml:space="preserve">West (Maghreb) › Tunisia › North Western Tunisia</p>
               <p>Bedouin-type dialect </p>
            </div>
            <div type="general">
               <p xml:space="preserve">Shikh el Widyan is a village located on the border between the governorates of Beja and Zaghouan in northwestern Tunisia, at a distance of 10 km from the town of <seg type="comment" xml:id="seg0"><ref target="comment0" type="noteAnchor">Gboullat</ref></seg>.</p>
               <p xml:space="preserve">The toponym Shikh el Widyan (“Sheik of the Rivers”) is possibly taken from the homonymous wadi Shikh el-Widyan which is situated near to this village.</p>
               <p xml:space="preserve">Concerning the population’s origin, some of the existing tribal groups are Bna Hmad (Bnǟ Ḥmad), Sebaa (is-Sibᵃʕ), Hamamma (l-ⁱHmǟmma), Hajr (il-Ḥažⁱṛ) as well as Ryah (ir-Ryǟḥ). As for the latter, according to local sources, they originate from the Hijaz, and they migrated to Tunisia via Egypt during the period of the Fatimid Caliphate. </p>
            </div>
            <div type="researchHistory">
               <p xml:space="preserve">To the best of our knowledge hitherto no research has been done on the dialect of Shikh el Widyan, however this dialect is linguistically investigated within the TUNOCENT project. </p>
            </div>
